caption:

caption:
#6 on the countdown is Italy. Every time I leave I want to plan another trip. What is your favorite city in Italy? 

There are so many different regions to explore and incredible landscapes to photograph in Italy. It's one of my favorite countries and a place I'll continue to return to my entire life.

caption:
France is #5! Every region here is unique and worthy of a visit. What's your favorite town in France? 

I really love this country and every time I visit I try to check out a new region. It's a great country for road trips through the countryside, delicious food, and incredible vineyards. But France is also packed with history, hiking trails, perfect coastal towns and mountains. That's why France makes the top 5 of my favorite countries.

caption: Colombia makes the #30countries30days list with incredible national parks, beautiful beaches and great cities to explore. It is home to 7 UNESCO World Heritage sites but there are dozens of sites worthy of the title. Pictured here is the coastal town of Cartagena which has a great old city to explore. It's an easy entry point before moving on to the bigger cities or national parks.

caption:
Just hit 30,000 so it's time for a Q&A! Ask me anything about travel and tell me about your plans for 2016. Where are you headed, where are you from, and what's your dream trip

I'm headed to Australia in February. In March I'm off to East Africa but more on that later. Tell me about your travel goals for 2016 and ask me anything you'd like

Thanks for following and supporting Triphackr! I'm always here to help you plan your next adventure.

comments.text: @sunnyrebeccamorris very cool. I like the idea of the Spanish immersion program. Happy to help. Are you booking this all on points and miles? Or just planning to book a long stopover? You can make either work you'll just have to get a little creative. Travel hacking is fun when you get the hang of it

@thelisette yeah, I had a full-time job and ran Triphackr on the side while traveling as much as possible. I ran the site for around 3.5 yrs before doing it full-time. I wouldn't have made the leap before I was ready but it's always a difficult decision to make. I'm sure this varies for all bloggers and how much they can dedicate to the site.

@triphackr 2016 will be : South Africa, Indonesia, East Africa, hong kong, Lebanon and my dream trip will be alaska. from St maarten, living now in Switzerland üá®üá≠ what did you like the most in Iran that could convince someone to go there?

How did the aspect of needing a private tour as a US citizen go?

@alecgrych visa process was very simple. I was required to have a guide at all times (who was excellent btw) but he gave me plenty of free time to explore on my own. It is not as strict as you think but for visa purposes necessary. Looking back I'm happy I had a guide even when it's not normally my thing. He was professional, very knowledgable, and a good friend by the end of the trip. I recommend it.

@alecgrych it's possible to get a visa that doesn't require a guide but difficult. You will likely need the help of some Iranian friends but I know people that do it that way. That would save you money. A tour will of course add a daily cost to your trip. Accommodation and transportation are very affordable to help balance things. The extra cost will depend on the level of tour you book.

caption:
Brazil is #1 and my favorite country in the world! Australia might challenge it next week but nothing beats caipirinhas on the beach!

I didn't post every country in the #30countries30days countdown but you can see the complete top 5 and top 30 on triphackr.com (the link is in my bio) 
It's almost impossible to pick a favorite country in the world but I have so many great memories from visiting Brazil since I first visited in '08 and will always return to see something new for the rest of my life

caption:
These Chimpanzees showed me the way home after we tracked them for a few hours. Watch my snap story (triphackr) for more but this was an incredible day and so much different than gorilla tracking. This is a raw and unedited video I shot after our time was almost up with the chimps (you are permitted one hour). Four chimps came up behind me on the trail, brushed my legs, and led the way out. I quickly had to get my camera back out and  follow them while keeping my distance

All four them walked in a line until they heard their friends in the distance and ran off to meet them. Seeing them in the wild is an amazing experience and Kibale National Park in Uganda is the perfect place to see them

The chimps are constantly on the move so once you find them you have to stay with them and follow them through the forest. It was a lot more challenging shooting them than the gorillas who tend to stay put once you locate them. The chimps are always on the move until they find some food or a nice place for a nap.

caption:
Unbelievable morning hanging out with these guys. I spent the morning tracking this family of mountain gorillas in Bwindi National Park in Uganda. These treks can take all morning or even all day but we ran into this family after only 30 minutes of hiking the steep terrain. All the credit goes to the amazing team of trackers that locate them every morning so we can have experiences like this

Since it's the low season there were only 3 of us total tracking today. I spent the morning with new friends @exploringkiwis who happened to be on my trek and I can't wait to see their photos too

Groups can be as large as 8 people and there is very limited space when tracking and photographing the gorillas. If you can get in a small group or risk the rains of the off season I recommend it. It's a much better gorilla tracking experience.

I just touched down in Bermuda in my new @ministryofsupply gear! I partnered up with @ministryofsupply this summer to test out their awesome gear. After this flight I can say these Aviator Chinos were definitely made with travelers in mind. Their mission is to make menswear smarter with technology with features like sweat-wicking fibers and body mapping ventilation. My first test results are in: I slept the entire flight and felt great on arrival. 
I'm always a bit skeptical when someone tells me that they're clothing is comfortable and great for travel but I loved these Bostonians story. When I learned they launched at MIT and the founder ran a half marathon in the clothes I knew I needed to try them for myself. 
Flying in clothes is my ultimate test. I always wear very comfortable clothing for flights and this outfit passed the test. If I didn't get yelled at for taking photos exiting the plane I'd probably be looking at the camera üòâ. Check out @ministryofsupply!

@triphackr photo spots: there are stereotypical (but must see) ones like: Victoria's Peak (take the tram up), giant Buddha (take the cable car ride, the scenery going over the mountains is stunning, but bundle up it gets cold up there!), take the star ferry back and forth between Hong Kong island and Kowloon (do it during the day and again at night for a diff view), the symphony of light show (best view is from the tsim sha tsui waterfront - u can take the star ferry), any one of the many wet markets, and then there's also Shek O beach which is popular with wedding photographers.  Happy Valley racecourse, I'm not sure if it's racing season but if it is you can get into the grounds on race night for HK$10 (cheap!) and get great pics of the horses barreling towards the finish line! (The local crowd really gets into it!)
Loved the #BigApple heli tour @atdattractions was amazing ! #NYC

@triphackr Food: there is every type imaginable in HK! try The Red Pepper restaurant for authentic Sichuan food. And Crystal Jade for quick, cheap noodles and xiaolongbao (both in Causeway bay). Maxims Palace in City Hall does a great dim sum in a beautiful/grand setting. American restaurant in wanchai - no frills setting but great peaking duck and sizzling lamb which you stuff into these great sesame seed bread pockets, yum. For Lebanese, my fave is Zahrabel dining club for real, homemade food (full disclosure: my friend runs it!).

caption: Guadeloupe is part of the French West Indies and made up of 5 islands. I didn't know what to expect before arriving but so far I'm really enjoying it.
